article.headline: Swoopes' jumper becomes the difference
article.linkText: Shock rally from 14 down, but Comets prevail at home
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes made sure the Houston Comets' home
losing streak didn't reach four.

Swoopes hit a 12-foot jumper with 23 seconds to play to give the
Comets a 62-61 victory over the Detroit Shock and end a franchise
record-tying three-game home losing streak.

The Comets led by 14 points in the second half, but fell behind
59-57 before rallying behind Swoopes and recently acquired Dawn
Staley.

One day after coming over in a trade from Charlotte, Staley hit
a long 3-pointer to give Houston a 60-59 lead with 2:46 left.
Swoopes, who finished with 17 points, hit her game-winner after
Deanna Nolan gave Detroit a 61-60 lead with 40 seconds left.

"We allowed them to get back in the game," Swoopes said. "We
had to fight to get back in it. We could have folded in the second
half, but we found a way to pull this one out."

Michelle Snow added 15 points and two blocks for the Comets
(15-10), who scored just 20 points in the second half. Tina
Thompson made two 3-pointers in the first half and finished with 10
points. Staley, coming off the bench for the first time in her
career, scored five points -- all in the final minutes.

"Detroit kind of took us out of rhythm that we had going for us
early in the game," Thompson added. "Our shots weren't falling in
the second half and we had to find a way to grind it out. We knew
it was going to be one of those games and thank goodness it turned
out in our favor."

Nolan scored 23 points for Detroit (10-13) and had a chance to
win the game with less than 2 seconds left, but her jumper glanced
off the front of the rim.

Cheryl Ford added 12 points for the Shock, who had won two
straight after losing five of six. Nolan scored nine points during
a 20-2 Detroit run after the Comets had taken a 44-30 lead early in
the second half on a jumper by Snow.

"I can't complain," Nolan said. "The last play started with a
good pass, but I came up just a little short. We fought back but we
couldn't get out of that hole we put ourselves in earlier in the
game."

The Shock led 52-46 after Ruth Riley's layup with 10:37 to go,
but Houston answered with an 11-3 run to take a 57-55 lead with
4:31 left. Staley's first points in her Comets' debut gave Houston
its first lead since 13:18. Detroit took a timeout and then scored
the next four points to take a 59-57 lead.

The Comets led 42-30 after an emotional first half as Swoopes
and Snow combined for 24 points. Houston opened a 26-13 lead before
the Shock used a 5-0 run to get within 26-19 with 5:22 left in the
half.

With 3:33 to go, double technical fouls were called on Snow and
Kara Braxton after Braxton was called for a hard foul and then
tangled with Snow.

Snow then jumped to her feet and took a half swing at Braxton.
Detroit head coach Bill Laimbeer was then called for an addition
technical foul for arguing with the officials.

"I was disappointed with the referee crew," Laimbeer said.
"They let things get out of hand. Snow took a swing on one of our
players and they called a double-technical on us.

"I feel sorry for them because they lied to me. They told me
that none of them saw it, but they all saw it and you just can't
take referees lying to you. It's just not right."

The Comets increased the lead to 34-21 as Swoopes and Snow
combined for four points on the play.

Detroit's Katie Smith, acquired from Minnesota last week, had
seven points in her second game with the Shock.
